definition.text: The elevation has been captured at the level of the maximum extent of the above ground envelope of the construction.

description.text: NOTE: The bottom of usable part of  a building is generally its lowest underground floor.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at the bottom of the usable part of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the entrance of the construction, generally the bottom of entrance door.

description.text: NOTE: in case of a roof having a symetry axis, values generalEave, lowestEave and highestEave are equivalent.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at eave level, anywhere between the lowest and the highest eave levels of the construction.

description.text: NOTE: In case of buildings located on flat areas, values generalGround, lowestgroundPoint and highestgroundPoint are equivalent.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at ground level, anywhere between the lowest and the highest ground points of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at roof level, anywhere between the lowest edge roof level and the top of the construction.

description.text: NOTE: in case of a roof having a symetry axis, values generalRoofEdge, lowestRoofEdge and highestRoofEdge are equivalent.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at roof edge level, anywhere between the lowest and the highest roof edges of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the highest eave level of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the highest ground point of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the highest point of the construction, including the installations, such as chimneys and antennas.
The elevation has been captured at the highest roof edge level of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the lowest eave level of the construction.

description.text: This value is of interest for over-hanging buildings or for buildings on pilotis.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at the level of the lowest floor above ground.
The elevation has been captured at the lowest ground point level of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the lowest roof edge level of the construction.

description.text: NOTE: for buildings, it is generally top of the roof.

definition.text: The elevation has been captured at the top level of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the highest ground point of the construction.
The elevation has been captured at the lowest ground point level of the construction.

description.text: NOTE: The values of this code list are used to describe the reference of elevation both where elevation has been captured as attribute or as Z coordinate.

definition.text: List of possible elements considered to capture a vertical geometry.
